list.name: Saudi Arabia
list.caption: Saudi Arabia produced 10.5 million barrels per day in 2010. Production has been stable but consumption is steadily rising. Net exports are in decline.

list.name: Russia
list.caption: Russia produced 10.1 million barrels per day in 2010. Production, consumption and net exports are steady. Data for Russia by itself are unavailable prior to the Soviet breakup.

list.name: United States
list.caption: United States produced 9.6 million barrels per day in 2010. Production is up slightly while consumption is down. The US is the #1 oil importer.

list.name: China
list.caption: China produced 4.3 million barrels per day in 2010. Production is still rising but cannot keep pace with consumption. Existing trends suggest that net imports will keep rising.

list.name: Iran
list.caption: Iran produced 4.3 million barrels per day in 2010. Production increases are barely keeping pace with increased consumption. Net exports are trending downward.

list.name: Canada
list.caption: Canada produced 3.5 million barrels per day in 2010. Production is up primarily due to increased tar sands production in Alberta.

list.name: Mexico
list.caption: Mexico produced 3.0 million barrels per day in 2010. Mexican production and net exports are down recently as the giant Cantarell field enters terminal decline.

list.name: UAE
list.caption: UAE produced 2.8 million barrels per day in 2010. Production is currently rising more slowly than consumption.

list.name: Brazil
list.caption: Brazil produced 2.7 million barrels per day in 2010. Production has risen sharply and Brazil is now a (small) net exporter.

list.name: Nigeria
list.caption: Nigeria produced 2.5 million barrels per day in 2010. Production, consumption and net exports are relatively stable.

list.name: Kuwait
list.caption: Kuwait produced 2.5 million barrels per day in 2010. Production has recently declined slightly. Oilfield damage resulting from the 1990 Iraqi invasion is obvious.

list.name: Iraq
list.caption: Iraq produced 2.4 million barrels per day in 2010. Iraq's production history is chaotic because of sanctions, war and ongoing dislocation. But consumption is steadily rising.

list.name: Venezuela
list.caption: Venezuela produced 2.4 million barrels per day in 2010. Production is in decline largely due to a lack of investment while consumption is steadily rising.

list.name: Norway
list.caption: Norway produced 2.1 million barrels per day in 2010. A perfect example of a geologically determined 'production peak'.

list.name: Algeria
list.caption: Algeria produced 2.1 million barrels per day in 2010. Production and net exports are up over the last decade.

list.name: Angola
list.caption: Angola produced 2.0 million barrels per day in 2010. Production and net exports are up significantly. Most production is located offshore.

list.name: Libya
list.caption: Libya produced 1.8 million barrels per day in 2010. The recent revolution in Lybia means that Lybian production and net exports will look very different for 2011.

list.name: Kazakhstan
list.caption: Kazakhstan produced 1.6 million barrels per day in 2010. Production and net exports are up significantly.

list.name: Qatar
list.caption: Qatar produced 1.4 million barrels per day in 2010. Better known for natural gas production, oil production is also up steeply in Qatar.

list.name: United Kingdom
list.caption: United Kingdom produced 1.4 million barrels per day in 2010. The Piper Alpha disaster in 1988 reduced offshore production for several years. Since 2000, UK oil fields have been in steady decline.

list.name: Azerbaijan
list.caption: Azerbaijan produced 1.0 million barrels per day in 2010. The world's first oil well was drilled in 1846 in Azerbaijan. Production and net exports are up significantly.

list.name: Indonesia
list.caption: Indonesia produced 1.0 million barrels per day in 2010. A classic example of the 'Export Land Model', production has fallen behind consumption and this previous OPEC member now imports oil.

list.name: India
list.caption: India produced 955 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Similar to China, Indian production is up only slightly in the face of rapidly increasing consumption.

list.name: Oman
list.caption: Oman produced 868 thousand barrels per day in 2010.

list.name: Colombia
list.caption: Colombia produced 801 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Production has risen recently and is anticipated to increase to 1.2 mbd by 2012.

list.name: Argentina
list.caption: Argentina produced 763 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Trends of declining production and increasing consumption look set to soon convert Argentina into a net importer.

list.name: Malaysia
list.caption: Malaysia produced 665 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Trends of declining production and increasing consumption look set to soon convert Malaysia into a net importer.

list.name: Egypt
list.caption: Egypt produced 663 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Egypt went from net exporter to net importer in 2009. The overthrow of the Mubarak regime occurred in 2010.

list.name: Australia
list.caption: Australia produced 550 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Net imports are on the rise.

list.name: Sudan
list.caption: Sudan produced 514 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Production and net exports are up significantly. The recent partition of North and South may impact this trend.

list.name: Ecuador
list.caption: Ecuador produced 486 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Since 2004, net exports have been in steady decline. The 1987 earthquake halved exports.

list.name: Syria
list.caption: Syria produced 401 thousand barrels per day in 2010. The production peak is evident but the events of 2011 will dramatically alter both production and consumption

list.name: Vietnam
list.caption: Vietnam produced 373 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Production has stabilized after a rapid rise but consuption is still rising. Net exports are in decline.

list.name: Thailand
list.caption: Thailand produced 343 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Production and consumption are both rising in this net oil importer.

list.name: Equatorial Guinea
list.caption: Equatorial Guinea produced 323 thousand barrels per day in 2010. The rapid rise in offshore production has now tapered off. The US is the #1 destination for Guinean oil.

list.name: Congo - Brazzaville
list.caption: Congo - Brazzaville produced 302 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Production has been rising. Consumption is still negligable.

list.name: Yemen
list.caption: Yemen produced 259 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Yemen is well past peak production. Current unrest will likely reduce production quantities.

list.name: Denmark
list.caption: Denmark produced 248 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Danish production displays a well defined peak. Net exports have entered a steady decline.

list.name: Gabon
list.caption: Gabon produced 228 thousand barrels per day in 2010.

list.name: Turkmenistan
list.caption: Turkmenistan produced 202 thousand barrels per day in 2010.

list.name: South Africa

list.name: Brunei

list.name: Peru
list.caption: Peru produced 158 thousand barrels per day in 2010.

list.name: Italy
list.caption: Italy produced 153 thousand barrels per day in 2010. With little production of their own, increasing prices in Italy are driving down consumption.

list.name: Germany
list.caption: Germany produced 148 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Germany is the #4 oil importer.

list.name: Trinidad and Tobago
list.caption: Trinidad and Tobago produced 145 thousand barrels per day in 2010.

list.name: Japan
list.caption: Japan produced 132 thousand barrels per day in 2010. In 2010 Japan was the #3 oil importer. In 2011 imports are rising due the closure of damaged nuclear plants.

list.name: Chad
list.caption: Chad produced 126 thousand barrels per day in 2010.

list.name: Romania
list.caption: Romania produced 107 thousand barrels per day in 2010. Romania was the most important source of oil for Nazi Germany but is now in long term decline.

list.name: East Timor

list.name: France
list.caption: France produced 84 thousand barrels per day in 2010. French consumption and imports of oil have been steady for almost three decades. France is the #7 oil importer.

list.name: Tunisia

list.name: Ukraine
